=========================================
1. What are STL Algorithms?
=========================================

STL Algorithms are generic functions that
operate on containers through iterators.

Examples:

sort(v.begin(), v.end());

find(v.begin(), v.end(), 10);

reverse(v.begin(), v.end());

Interview Answer:

STL algorithms are reusable generic
functions that work with containers
through iterators.

=========================================
2. sort() (MOST ASKED)
=========================================

Used to sort elements.

Example:

sort(v.begin(), v.end());

Ascending order.

-----------------------------------------

Descending Order

sort(v.begin(),
     v.end(),
     greater<int>());

-----------------------------------------

Complexity

O(n log n)

-----------------------------------------

Requirement

Random Access Iterators required.

Works:

✔ vector
✔ deque
✔ array

Does NOT work:

✘ set
✘ map
✘ list

=========================================
3. find()
=========================================

Searches for an element.

Example:

auto it = find(v.begin(),
               v.end(),
               20);

If found:
---------
it points to element

If not found:
-------------
it == v.end()

Complexity:

O(n)

=========================================
4. count()
=========================================

Counts occurrences.

Example:

count(v.begin(),
      v.end(),
      10);

Complexity:

O(n)

=========================================
5. reverse()
=========================================

Reverses elements.

Example:

reverse(v.begin(),
        v.end());

Complexity:

O(n)

=========================================
6. binary_search()
=========================================

Checks whether element exists.

Example:

binary_search(v.begin(),
              v.end(),
              20);

Returns:

true / false

-----------------------------------------

Requirement

Range must be sorted.

Complexity:

O(log n)

=========================================
7. lower_bound()
=========================================

Returns iterator to:

First element >= value

Example:

vector<int> v =
{10,20,20,30};

auto it =
lower_bound(v.begin(),
            v.end(),
            20);

Result:

Points to first 20

-----------------------------------------

Complexity

O(log n)

-----------------------------------------

Requirement

Sorted range required.

=========================================
8. upper_bound()
=========================================

Returns iterator to:

First element > value

Example:

vector<int> v =
{10,20,20,30};

auto it =
upper_bound(v.begin(),
            v.end(),
            20);

Result:

Points to 30

-----------------------------------------

Complexity

O(log n)

=========================================
9. Difference Between lower_bound and upper_bound
=========================================

Data:

10 20 20 20 30

lower_bound(20)
---------------
First element >= 20

Points to first 20

upper_bound(20)
---------------
First element > 20

Points to 30

Very common interview question.

=========================================
10. How To Count Duplicates In Sorted Array?
=========================================

Frequency:

upper_bound() - lower_bound()

Example:

10 20 20 20 30

Frequency of 20:

3

=========================================
11. min_element()
=========================================

Returns iterator to minimum element.

Example:

*min_element(v.begin(),
             v.end());

Complexity:

O(n)

=========================================
12. max_element()
=========================================

Returns iterator to maximum element.

Example:

*max_element(v.begin(),
             v.end());

Complexity:

O(n)

=========================================
13. Why Doesn't sort() Work On list?
=========================================

sort() requires Random Access Iterators.

list provides:

Bidirectional Iterator

Therefore:

sort(list.begin(), list.end());

Compilation Error.

Use:

list.sort();

Interview favorite.

=========================================
14. Difference Between find() and binary_search()
=========================================

find():
-------
Works on any range

O(n)

-----------------------------------------

binary_search():
----------------
Requires sorted range

O(log n)

Returns bool

Very common question.

=========================================
15. Difference Between count() and find()
=========================================

find():
-------
Returns iterator

Used to check existence

-----------------------------------------

count():
--------
Returns frequency

